#Introduction This is a study of regression on a real data set in order to predict the unleaded gasoline sales for the upcoming 4 periods. The abbreviations for the variable names of the data set are present below. The study aims to investigate the relationship between the independent variables and the target variable so that a prediction model could be formed.

UGS: Unleaded gasoline sale in a given quarter(output variable),
RNUV: An index indicating the rate of new unleaded gasoline using vehicles being added to the traffic in a quarter,
PU: Average price (adjusted with an index) of a liter of unleaded gasoline in a quarter,
PG: Average price (adjusted with an index) of a liter of diesel gasoline in a quarter,
NUGV: Number of unleaded gasoline using vehicles in the traffic,
NDGV: Number of diesel gasoline using vehicles in the traffic (per 1000 people),
GNPA: Agriculture component of Gross National Product (adjusted with an index),
GNPC: Commerce component of Gross National Product (adjusted with an index),
GNP: Grand total for GNP (agriculture, commerce and other components total).

#Analyzing the data When the csv document is transferred to the data object, it has been observed that there are several variables such as the target variable(shown above as Unleaded.Gasoline.Sale..UGS.) that have chr type. The variable is a numeric variable therefore it must be converted to numeric format within the other variables that require the same change.

for(i in 1:32){
  for(j in 2:11)
  data[i,j] <- as.numeric(gsub(" ","",data[i,j]))
}

for(i in 2:11){
  data[,i] <- as.numeric(data[,i])
}

##Adding some columns to the data set The data set has been provided with the trend and seasonality columns to find a coefficient corresponding to these components. Also, the quarter variable has been transformed to factor type since it is not a numeric variable. It has also been seen that the acf of lag 1 and lag 4 variables seem to be significant. Therefore, they are added on the data set to be added into the model.

for(i in 1:28){

for(i in 1:28){
  data$lag4[i+4] = data$Unleaded.Gasoline.Sale..UGS.[i]
}

In the model, it has been seen that the lag4 values p value is low. This could be due to the fact that lag1 is explaining the lag4s effect. There could be multi-collinearity between these variables. Further investigation is going to be done regarding which variables to be removed via correlation plot of the ggcorrplot function.

new_data <- data[!is.na(data$Unleaded.Gasoline.Sale..UGS. & data$lag1 & data$lag4),]

corr = cor(new_data[,unlist(lapply(new_data, is.numeric))])

ggcorrplot(corr,
           hc.order = TRUE,
           type='lower',
           lab=TRUE)

Here, the remark regarding the two relations should be made. Firstly, the relationship between the lag4 and seasonality terms are probably quite high since the lag-1 variable and lag-4 variables correlation information is not high[0.3]. Also, the price of unleaded gasoline is highly correlated with the price of diesel gasoline therefore one is explained quite well by the other. Since the variable were interested in is related to unleaded gasoline, the diesel gasoline regressor is going to be removed from the model first. It will be investigated that whether theres an improvement in adjusted R2. Also, lag-4 variable will be removed from the model due to the low p-value.

checkresiduals(model4)

## 
## data:  Residuals
## LM test = 20.476, df = 12, p-value = 0.05859

The residuals seem to be distributed with constant mean(0) and constant variance. Also, they seem to be distributed normally as seen from the plot at the right bottom and Breusch-Godfrey tests p-value. ACF shows an almost significant value at lag-4 but weve encountered this issue. The addition of lag-4 variable to the model decreases the adjusted R2 and the variable is not an important variable. The model seems to be delicate.

plot(model4)

The model seems to be well fit.

##Forecasting

predictions = c()
for(i in 1:4){
  predictions[i] = predict(model4,newdata=data[i+28,])
  if(28 < 32-i){
    data$lag1[i+29] = predictions[i]
  }
}
predictions
## [1] 662492.3 845565.1 965974.6 788131.3

Predictions are present above. The model seems to be well fit.

##Conclusion The model is built through going a trial and error process. The best model is found with respect to the highest adjusted R2 metric. The predictions for the upcoming four periods are present above.
